# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ferret-legging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Historically in the West Riding of Yorkshire, Barnsley is located on the M1 corridor between the cities of Sheffield to the south and Wakefield to the north.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Doncaster lies to the east, Huddersfield to the north-west and Manchester lies west across the Peak District, to which it is connected via the A628 road.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley's former industries include linen, coal mining, glass making and textiles.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Its culture is rooted in its industrial heritage and has a tradition of brass bands, originally created as social clubs by its mining communities.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The name Barnsley derives from the Old English *Beornslēah* meaning 'Beorn's wood or clearing'.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Following the Norman invasion of 1066, many abbeys and priories were built in Yorkshire.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Norman landowners increased their revenues and established new towns such as Barnsley, Doncaster, Hull, Leeds, Scarborough and Sheffield.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Of towns founded before the conquest, only Bridlington, Pocklington, and York continued at a prominent level.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Although settlements had been established in the Barnsley area for centuries prior, and was a well known centre to trade, the first reference to Barnsley occurs in 1086 in the *Domesday Book*, in which it is called *Berneslai* and has a population of around 200.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town was in the parish of Silkstone and developed little until in the 1150s, when it was given to the Pontefract Priory.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The monks built a town where three roads met: the Sheffield to Wakefield, Rotherham to Huddersfield and Cheshire to Doncaster routes.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Domesday village became known as Old Barnsley, and a town grew up on the new site.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The monks erected a chapel of ease dedicated to Saint Mary, which survived until 1820 , and established a market.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In 1249, a Royal charter was granted to Barnsley permitting it to hold a weekly market on Wednesdays and annual four-day fair at Michaelmas.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] By the 1290s, three annual fairs were held.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town was the centre of the Staincross wapentake but, in the mid-16th century, it had only 600 inhabitants.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] From the 17th century, Barnsley developed into a stop-off point on the route between Leeds, Wakefield, Sheffield and London.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The traffic generated as a result of its location fuelled trade, with hostelries and related services prospering.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] A principal centre for linen-weaving during the 18th and 19th century, Barnsley grew into an important manufacturing town.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The first passenger station to serve Barnsley was opened by the North Midland Railway in 1840.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley station (later called Cudworth) was located some 2+1⁄2 miles (4 km) away at Cudworth.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] On 1 January 1850, the Manchester and Leeds Railway opened Barnsley Exchange station, close to the town centre.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] On 1 May 1870, the Midland Railway opened Regent Street station, a temporary structure.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] A new station was opened by the MR on the Regent Street site on 23 August 1873.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] As it incorporated the old court house in its construction, Regent Street station was renamed Barnsley Court House.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley became a municipal borough in 1869 and a county borough in 1913.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town's boundaries were extended to absorb Ardsley and Monk Bretton in 1921, and Carlton in 1938.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town was the site of a human crush that resulted in the deaths of 16 children in 1908 at a public hall, now known as The Civic, when children were rushing to watch a film in the building.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley has a long tradition of glass-making, however Barnsley is most famous for its coal mines.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In 1960, there were 70 collieries within a 15 miles (24 km) radius of Barnsley town centre, but the last of these closed in 1994.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The National Union of Mineworkers still has its HQ in Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] George Orwell mentioned the town in *The Road to Wigan Pier*.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] He arrived in the town on 11 March 1936 and spent a number of days living in the houses of the working class miners, while researching for the book.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] He wrote very critically of the council's expenditure on the construction of Barnsley Town Hall and claimed that the money should have been spent on improving the housing and living conditions of the local miners.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town hall itself is visible behind some gardens; the building is made of white stone and has an impressive clock tower.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Opened on 14 December 1933, Barnsley Town Hall is the seat of local government in the Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The County Borough of Barnsley was created in 1913, administered independently of the West Riding of Yorkshire.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Elections to Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council have seen the Labour Party retain control of the council at every election until 2026, when Reform UK won a majority of the seats.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Following the latest election in 2026 the council has 42 Reform, 11 Labour, and 8 Liberal Democrat, and 2 Independent councillors.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The borough council elects the mayor every year.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] On the day of the election, a parade takes place in front of the town hall in honour of the new mayor.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The metropolitan borough is split into four parliamentary constituencies, all represented by the following Labour Party MPs: Barnsley North by Dan Jarvis, Barnsley South by Stephanie Peacock, Penistone and Stocksbridge by Marie Tidball, and Wentworth and Dearne, by John Healey.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley is located in the valley of the River Dearne at the eastern foothills of the Pennines, near the uplands of the Peak District to the west.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Geologically, the town is located within the area of the South Yorkshire Coalfield, consisting of the middle coal measures and sandstones laid down in the Carboniferous period.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town lies approximately 12 miles (19 km) north of Sheffield, 17 miles (27 km) south of Leeds, 9 miles (14 km) south of Wakefield and 32 miles (51 km) east of Manchester.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley is within a green belt region that extends into the borough and wider surrounding counties.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It is in place to reduce urban sprawl, prevent the towns in the Barnsley/Dearne Valley conurbation from further convergence, protect the identity of outlying communities, encourage brownfield reuse and preserve nearby countryside.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] This is achieved by restricting inappropriate development within the designated areas, and imposing stricter conditions on permitted building.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The green belt surrounds the Barnsley built-up area, separating towns and villages throughout the borough.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Larger outlying communities such as Cudworth, Dodworth, Kendray, Monk Bretton and Worsbrough are also exempt from the green belt area.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] However, nearby smaller villages, hamlets and rural areas such as Swaithe, Smithley, Low Laithes and Upper Norcroft are 'washed over' by the designation.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Much semi-rural land on the fringes is also included.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The green belt was first defined in 1979, and the area in 2017 amounted to some 23,050 hectares (230.5 km2; 89.0 sq mi), 77% of the borough.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] A subsidiary aim of the green belt is to encourage recreation and leisure interests, with rural landscape features, greenfield areas and facilities.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Beyond Penistone, the green belt also borders the Peak District National Park.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town's population was recorded as 71,599 at the 2021 census, while the wider borough (as of 2025) has a population of 251,770.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Previously, 2011 census data showed the town was 94.7% White British, 1.1% Asian and 0.8% Black.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] A large part of Barnsley town centre was constructed during the 1960s.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The area around Cheapside and May Day Green, the Metropolitan Centre, is home to the market and many national high street chains.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Alhambra Shopping Centre, which was opened in 1991, houses several retailers.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Other prominent areas include Queen Street, Market Street, Eldon Street and the Victorian Arcade, which houses the majority of the independent and designer retailers in Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town also has a large concentration of pubs and bars in the central district.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] There is also a twin auditorium cinema called Parkway Cinema Barnsley occupying what once was the Odeon Cinema on Eldon Street.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The development of a new shopping centre was started in the town centre in late 2015.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Major companies in Barnsley include on-line retailer ASOS; the largest cake bakery in Europe, Premier Foods (formerly Lyons Bakery) which makes the Mr Kipling Cake brand; Ardagh Glass, glass bottle makers; Symphony Kitchens; and Premdor.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Most of these businesses are based on industrial parks outside the town centre, including many on reclaimed former coal mine sites.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town centre is now moving towards a service economy.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In June 2024, unemployment stood at 3.4% in Barnsley North and 4.1% in Barnsley South, compared to the national level of 3.9%.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The western half of the borough stretches from the M1 to the edge of the Peak District and is rural in character.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] This western part includes the market town of Penistone and Wentworth Castle and its Grade I listed gardens, Cannon Hall Park and Museum, Cawthorne Jubilee Museum, Wortley Hall and gardens, and Wortley Top Forge (16th century Forge).
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In 2002, Barnsley Council and partners launched a consultation, "Rethinking Barnsley".
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It led to a regeneration programme centred on the town centre which is still underway.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Developments included the transport interchange, a cultural centre in the old Civic Hall, a Digital Media Centre (opened August 2007), and new offices and apartments throughout the town centre.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] At the same time new housing areas were developed.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Business parks on the M1 at Junctions 37 and 36, and in the Dearne Valley, have expanded job opportunities.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Unemployment is now below the national average.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The economic development of Barnsley is led by the Barnsley Development Agency.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town was known for a thriving linen trade prior to the arrival of the coal industry.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] From the 1850s onwards, a large number of coal pits were opened, mostly in the villages surrounding the town, especially those to the east.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Coal mining was the major industry of the town until the late 1950s, when a long-term decline set in.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] All the mines in the borough are now closed, the last to shut being Goldthorpe Colliery in 1994.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Wire, linen and glass making were also major industries, but only glass making remains, with one company still operating.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The coat of arms for the town has both a coal miner and a glass-blower supporting a shield and depicting local families and other industries, above a ribbon bearing the town's motto, *Spectemur agendo* ("Let us be judged by our acts").
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The first bottle bank for glass recycling collection in the United Kingdom was introduced by both Stanley Race CBE, then president of the Glass Manufacturers' Federation and major employer Redfearn's (now Ardagh Glass) and Ron England in Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The bottle bank opened on 24 August 1977.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The main transport hub is Barnsley Interchange, a combined railway and bus station that was opened on 20 May 2007; it was the first project of the *Remaking Barnsley* scheme.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Stagecoach Yorkshire operates most bus services within the borough, operating from the interchange.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Routes connect the town with Sheffield, Doncaster, Rotherham and Penistone.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Passenger services are provided by Northern Trains on the Hallam and Penistone Lines.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Routes connect the town with Leeds, Castleford, Nottingham, Lincoln, Sheffield and Huddersfield.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Since the closure of Robin Hood Airport, the nearest airport is Leeds Bradford, approximately 31 miles (50 km) away.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley College is situated on a number of sites throughout the town centre, chiefly Old Mill Lane campus, SciTech Centre, Honeywell sports campus, CUBE Construction Centre and STEM Centre.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The University of Huddersfield has recently opened a campus in the town on Church Street, beside Barnsley Town Hall; this is known as the University Campus Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] All 14 secondary schools in Barnsley were demolished and replaced by academy education centres, named *SuperSchools*.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] These combined all the previous LEA run comprehensive schools in the area into newly PFI built academies under the Building Schools for the Future programme.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Civic, in the town centre, is a multi-purpose performance venue in a grade II listed building.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The building was originally the Barnsley Mechanics Institute and Public Hall, built by Henry Harvey in 1877.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] His brother Charles Harvey, gave the building to the people of the town a few years later, renaming it the Harvey Institute.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Harvey Institute was host to many types of entertainment, including variety shows and cinema.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It was also home to the public library and shops; public meetings and celebrations were held in the hall; and education was provided.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The School of Art occupied the Public Hall from 1878 to 1948, which was also used as first headquarters and billets for "Barnsley Pals" during World War I.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In 1962, the building became Barnsley Civic Theatre, closing in 1998.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Civic was reopened in March 2009 after a major redevelopment, which included provision for a theatre and public art gallery.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Civic has hosted high-profile acts such as Al Murray and Russell Howard.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Civic houses a contemporary art gallery that hosts touring exhibition from the V&A and the Flow Gallery in London.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Civic also curates its own work for touring.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Lamproom Theatre has four theatrical companies, and showcases theatre in the town.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Academy Theatre is part of the Take 2 Centre, where performances range from comedy to musicals.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The Take 2 Centre houses The Take 2 Performing Arts Academy, The Stage Door Restaurant, and The Take 2 Music Centre.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley Council operates five museums: Elsecar Heritage Centre, Cannon Hall, the Cooper Gallery Worsbrough Mill and Experience Barnsley, which opened in the Town Hall in 2015.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Other museums in Barnsley include the volunteer-run Darfield Museum and the Cawthorne Victoria Jubilee Museum.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Other heritage sites include Wortley Top Forge, Wortley Hall, Wentworth Castle, Monk Bretton Priory and Pot House Hamlet.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] HIVE Gallery is a contemporary art gallery set up in 2007.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It is in Elsecar Heritage Centre and puts on eight contemporary art exhibitions per year.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The HIVE programme ranges from supporting emerging contemporary artists to exhibiting the work of nationally and internationally known artists.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley is home to a tradition of brass bands, which were originally created as social clubs for the mining communities.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Grimethorpe Colliery Band, located in Grimethorpe, 5 miles (8 km) to the east of Barnsley, is perhaps the best known brass band in Britain.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It rose to fame in the film *Brassed Off* and is now the 'artist in residence' at the Royal College of Music, London.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The band has performed in Hyde Park during the Last Night of the Proms.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Other events include Picnic In The Park, being held annually to raise funds for Barnsley Hospice.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] There is a live rock and hip hop music scene, which reached its height in the Britpop years, around 1997, due to its close proximity to Sheffield and Manchester.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The 1980s saw the rise of Saxon (metal band), Danse Society (Goth) and Party Day (Indie-rock).
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Both Alex Turner and Matt Helders, of the Arctic Monkeys, studied music at Barnsley College.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley is the home of several live music venues such as The Underground, The Garrison, The Old No 7 and The Old School House.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It formerly hosted the Barnsley Origin Music festival (BOMfest), an outdoor summer music festival which catered for local and national artists.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It now hosts Barnsley Live, an annual music festival featuring local acts that takes place in the town centre over a weekend in June, until it was announced to no longer go on by festival organisers in 2025.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In December 2023, a Christmas carol, written by local musician Arthur Godfrey in 1933, was rediscovered in the archives of the *Barnsley Chronicle*.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It was rerecorded to celebrate the 90th birthday of the town hall.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The "Bard of Barnsley" Ian McMillan writes a column in the *Barnsley Chronicle*.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] He was nominated for a chair of poetry at Oxford University and appears on BBC Radio 4.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] It was reported that Barnsley is the most frequently defined sub-Yorkshire dialect in interviews on attitudes to local dialects, with the fronted [a:] in the first syllable of the town's name often cited.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] An article in the Transactions of the Yorkshire Dialect Society noted that it is a relatively recent notion that Barnsley is distinctive and that most traditional dialect writing saw Barnsley as much the same as neighbouring areas of the West Riding.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The developers of the 2024 adventure game *Thank Goodness You're Here!* are from Barnsley and serves as the primary basis for the game's setting of Barnsworth.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Regional television is provided by BBC Yorkshire and ITV Yorkshire.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Television signals are received from the Emley Moor TV transmitter.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Local radio stations are BBC Radio Sheffield, Greatest Hits Radio South Yorkshire, Heart Yorkshire, Capital Yorkshire and Hits Radio South Yorkshire.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Barnsley F.C. play in League One, the third tier of English football.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Their home ground, Oakwell Stadium is situated in Oakwell, just outside the town centre.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The club has had a mixed recent history.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] In the late 1990s, they had a brief spell in the Premier League, but were relegated after one season.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Subsequent seasons saw them relegated to the third tier of English football; they were promoted to the second tier in 2006, beating Swansea in the play off final.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] They were relegated in the 2013–14 season.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] After two seasons, Barnsley regained a place in the second tier, following a victory at Wembley in the 2016 Football League One play-off final, and the winners of the 2016 Football League Trophy Final.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] They were again relegated to the third tier at the end of the 2017–18 season.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Also in Barnsley, there is a women's football team called Barnsley WFC, who currently play in the North East Regional Women's Football League Premier Division.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Speedway racing was staged at a track near Barnsley at Lundwood.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The track entered a team in the Northern Leagues of 1929 and 1930.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Two-time British Under-21 Championship rider Josh Bates hails from the town.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Greyhound racing was held at Dillington Park Stadium from 1934 -1990 and at the Dearne Athletic and Sports Stadium in Old Mill Lane, from 1934 to 1935.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] A third venue at the Queen's Ground was refused three times by the Corporation in 1936.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Shaw Lane is the home to many sports in town, cricket, rugby union, squash, bowls, football, athletics and archery are all played to a high standard and host many of the towns teams including Barnsley CC and Barnsley RUFC.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Peoples Sport in Barnsley is a project writing the history of participation in sport in Barnsley is in progress and is expected to be complete in 2015.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The town is home to Barnsley Harriers, a nationally recognised running club, and a high standard badminton league, with three separate tiers.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Ardsley Golf Club first appeared in the 1930s.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The club disappeared at the onset of the Second World War.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] Golf can still be played at Hillies in Wombwell and there is also a driving range at Staincross.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] There are a number of cycling clubs, including Barnsley Road Club itself, the long-established Birdwell Wheelers and Team Cystic Fibrosis (a charity-focused team), together covering many different forms of cycle sport and leisure.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] There have also been various other initiatives set up to promote cycling in the town and district of Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/barnsley] The following people, military units and organisations and groups have received the Freedom of the Town of Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Described by *The New York Times* as a "robust character actor" who played "gruff but likable roles", he had a "string of roles playing tough guys and criminals".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He once said, "You play to your strengths in this game, and my strength is as a bald-headed, rough-looking Yorkshireman".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover was also known as the voice of Gaffer in the Tetley tea commercials.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] *The Independent* described him upon his death as "one of Britain's best-loved actors".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover was born at the Women's Hospital, Sheffield, West Riding of Yorkshire and he lived in Sheffield until 1937 when his parents moved to Lundwood, near Barnsley.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] His father, Charles Glover, was a wrestler, performing as "the Red Devil".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He attended Barnsley Grammar School and the University of Sheffield, where he supplemented his student grant with appearances as a professional wrestler, going under the ring name "Leon Arras the Man From Paris".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He adopted that name from a wrestler who did not turn up to a match one night, for whom Glover stood in.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] His wrestling style incorporated a lot of comedy, including the catchphrases "ask 'im, ref" and "'ow about that then".
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] In 1954 he married his first wife, Elaine Foster, and became a teacher at the same Barnsley school where he had been a pupil.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He taught English and French from 1954 until 1970, some of it at Longcar Central School, Barnsley, where he met Barry Hines, who was also teaching there.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He managed to combine this with regular performances as "Leon Arras", whose appearances included bouts on *World of Sport*, and in Paris, Milan, Zürich and Barcelona.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover's first acting role came playing Mr Sugden, the comically overbearing sports teacher in Ken Loach's film *Kes* (a job offered to him when Barry Hines, who wrote the film, suggested him to the director).
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Although untrained, Glover proved to be a skilled and flexible character actor, using techniques learnt during his wrestling career.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] His large bald head, stocky build, and distinctive voice, with his Yorkshire accent, garnered him many roles as tough guys and criminals.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He played Bottom in *A Midsummer Night's Dream* (BBC TV, 1981) and had a recurring role in the classic sitcom *Porridge* as dim-witted prison inmate Cyril Heslop who, when accused of being illiterate, utters the memorable line "I read a book once!
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He also appeared in *An American Werewolf in London*, *The First Great Train Robbery*, *Jabberwocky*, *Alien 3*, *Leon the Pig Farmer* and as General Douglas in a Bollywood hit *1942: A Love Story*.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He appeared seven times in *Play for Today*, in three of them as part of a recurring trio of Yorkshiremen: *The Fishing Party*, *Shakespeare or Bust* and *Three for the Fancy*.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover's performance in *Kes* led to parts at the Royal Court Theatre, London, notably in Lindsay Anderson's *The Changing Room* (1971).
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] A season with Britain's Royal Shakespeare Company followed, where his roles included Charles the wrestler (and, drawing on his wrestling experience, the fight arranger) in *As You Like It*, and a robust Peter in *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] For the Royal National Theatre he appeared in *The Mysteries* (as God, creating the world with the help of a real fork-lift truck), *Saint Joan* and *Don Quixote*.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] In the film *Brannigan* he claimed to have lost the only fight in his acting career, fighting John Wayne.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] His performance in *The Mysteries* secured additional work in the commercial theatre.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] *The Canterbury Tales* ("Chaucer wi' nowt taken owt")(West End) was followed by a return to television and the *Play for Today* series, both as writer and performer and, in turn, more screen roles.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover wrote a horror themed episode of *Theatre Box* called *Death Angel*, which aired in 1981.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He went on to play Lugg, the endearing rogue manservant to Albert Campion in the series *Campion*, and the role of a crook, Griffiths, in the *Doctor Who* story *Attack of the Cybermen* in 1985.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He played Edouard Dindon in the original London cast of *La Cage aux Folles*.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] In 1991 he guest starred in the second episode of *Bottom*, in the episode "Gas", as the hostile neighbour Mr Rottweiler.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] At the end of his life he acted in John Godber's rugby league comedy *Up 'n' Under* (1998).
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He was also the voice for the UNO Upholstery TV adverts in 1995 and 1996.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover also wrote over twenty plays and short films.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] In 1982 he was a guest presenter in series six of *Friday Night Saturday Morning*, a late-night BBC chat show.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] Glover was married twice, secondly to television producer Tara Prem, the daughter of TV actor Bakhshi Prem, on 2 October 1976.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He had two children, one daughter from his first marriage and one son from his second marriage.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] In September 1996, Glover developed a brain tumour and underwent an operation for it.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] The tumour was removed and it appeared he had made a full recovery but it returned in the summer of 1997 and Glover died in his sleep in a London hospital on 24 July 1997.
[src:ferret-legging/brian-glover] He was buried in Brompton Cemetery, London, on 30 July 1997.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The **California State Lottery** began in October 1985 after voters authorized it in Proposition 37, the California State Lottery Act of 1984.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] It offers a range of games including number draws, scratchcards and a mock horse race.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The earnings provide supplementary funding for public education.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The Lottery Act was intended to provide more money to schools without imposing extra taxes.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Accordingly, the Lottery was required to provide at least 34% of its revenues to public education, supplementing (not replacing) other funds provided by California.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Another 50% of its revenues must be paid to the public in the form of prizes, making a mandated minimum of 84% of all funds that must be given back to the public in the form of prizes or funds for public education.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The remainder, a maximum of 16%, was to be spent on administration, such as salaries and running the games.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] On April 8, 2010, Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger signed into law Assembly Bill 142 (Hayashi, D-Hayward).
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Amending the Lottery Act, this bill reallocates Lottery revenues "so as to maximize the amount of funding allocated to public education." As an urgency statute, this bill took effect immediately.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The new allocation increased to at least 87% the portion of Lottery revenue returned to the public, and correspondingly decreased to a maximum of 13% the amount spent on administration.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The Lottery Act mandates a five-member commission, appointed by the governor, to "oversee the Lottery and the Director" and make quarterly reports "to the Governor, the Attorney General, the Controller, the Treasurer, and the Legislature." Annually the commission selects a chairperson.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Regular meetings of the commission are held at least quarterly and are open to the public.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] George Deukmejian appointed the first Lottery commissioners: William Johnston, Laverta Montgomery, John Price, Howard Varner, and Kennard Webster.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Deukmejian appointed the first director, Mark Michalko, formerly Ohio Lottery legal counsel, in May 1985.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] On 12 March 2012, Governor Jerry Brown appointed Gregory J.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Ahern to the commission, who was also elected as Sheriff of Alameda County in 2006.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The Lottery Act of 1984 was presented to voters in November of that year as a ballot proposition, Proposition 37, and passed with 58% of the vote.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The Act mandated an extremely tight timeline for establishing the Lottery and bringing it to operational status.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] To comply, the state government immediately built the Lottery's original headquarters in only three months in the Richards neighborhood of Sacramento (just north of downtown).
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Governor Deukmejian appointed the Lottery's first director, Mark Michalko, formerly Ohio Lottery legal counsel, in May 1985.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The first lottery games were Scratchers; sales began on October 3, 1985.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A weekly Lotto game began a year later on October 14, 1986.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Games hosted by the California Lottery include MEGA Millions, Super Lotto Plus, Fantasy 5, Daily 4, Daily 3, Daily Derby, and Scratchers.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In a true "lottery", the players play against each other; in a "banked game", they play each other *and* against the house.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The critical distinction between the two is that a bank in a "banked game" can be broken based purely upon whether each of the individual bets is won or lost; the house unconditionally promises to pay prizes on all winning bets with no maximum ceiling.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The high court explained that while this definition of a lottery does not prohibit fixed-prize lotteries, such lotteries are valid only if the total prize amount and the maximum number of fixed prizes to be won are fixed before the draw.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Subsequently, California Attorney General Dan Lungren also ruled that Daily 3, which at the time had fixed payouts, also was illegal because it created an interest on the part of the state that fewer people should win, contrary to a lottery where the operator has no stake in the outcome of the draw.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In response to these rulings, the Lottery modified Keno and created Hot Spot, which has a pari-mutuel payout format, and modified Daily 3 to a pari-mutuel format where payouts vary depending on the number of individuals who picked the winning numbers.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California joined Mega Millions on June 22, 2005; it became the 12th jurisdiction to offer the game, and the last to join before the 2010 cross-sell expansion with Multi-State Lottery Association (MUSL).
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A Mega Millions drawing was held in Hollywood to commemorate the event.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In September 2011, the California Lottery moved into a new $58 million headquarters at 700 North 10th Street right next to the old one, which was promptly demolished.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Because the original headquarters was built in a frantic 90-day rush to comply with the Lottery Act, it suffered from numerous construction defects in the roof, foundation, and elevator, as well as a mold problem.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California, while initially never desiring to offer Mega Millions's rival Powerball, was briefly a member of the MUSL because an "international" lottery game that would have included a number of US lotteries was planned; however, the game never came to fruition.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] However, in February 2012 the California Lottery initiated an impact analysis of the Powerball game, in preparation for a recommendation in July 2012.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Subsequently, the Fiscal Year 2012–2013 Business Plan included funding for a launch of Powerball within the fiscal year, with Powerball launching in California on April 8, 2013.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] As a result of the California Supreme Court's decision, California is the only state with variable payouts for both games.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Playing Daily 3 involves picking three digits 0 through 9 and a playstyle.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Bettors can choose Quick Pick to have the numbers picked randomly by computer.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The playstyle choices are straight (this is the default if the player doesn't choose one) box, or straight/box.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The game costs $1 per play, per draw, and the Advance Play option allows up to 14 consecutive draws.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] There are two draws every day, televised at 1:29pm and 6:59pm.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A "pick 4" type game premiered on May 19, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Each play costs $1 and drawings are held once per day.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Daily Derby is a mock horse racing game.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Players choose three horses out of 12, one each to finish first (win), second (place) and third (show); players also choose a race time from 1:40:00 to 1:49:99, by marking the last three digits of the time on the playslip.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Alternately, players can select Quick Pick to have the computer choose the horses, the race time, or both.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Daily Derby also offers Advance Play for up to 14 consecutive draws.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The game costs $2 per play, per draw; held daily at 6:35pm and televised at 6:59pm.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Fantasy 5 players choose five numbers from 1 through 39.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A ticket includes up to five sets of numbers; they can be played up to 12 drawings.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Fantasy 5 is drawn evenings at 6:35pm and televised at 6:59pm.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The starting jackpot ranges between $60,000 and $80,000.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Players can win by matching 2, 3, 4, or all 5 numbers in any order with the numbers selected on their fantasy 5 tickets.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A player who bought a $5 Fantasy 5 ticket used to get a coupon to mail in for a "second-chance" drawing to be on the *Make Me a Millionaire* show, or to play the Dream Machine on the first TV show, *The Big Spin*.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] That drawing was cancelled in July 2010 and now players receive a "second-chance" coupon with a twenty digit code.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Players can enter those codes at www.calottery.com/fan5 to be entered into a weekly drawing for a cash prize ranging from $1,000 to $10,000.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] SuperLotto Plus is a lotto game played in the style of Mega Millions and Powerball.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] SuperLotto Plus is drawn every Wednesday and Saturday.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The game began in 1986 as Lotto 6/49 (which was played similarly to the Canadian version of the game), then changed to SuperLotto somewhere in the 90s (with the matrix of 6/51).
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In 2000, the name was changed to SuperLotto Plus.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Its starting jackpot is $7 million (annuitized); a cash option is available for jackpot winners.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] SuperLotto Plus players choose five numbers from 1 through 47, and one Mega Ball number from 1 through 27.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] While the cash option usually is chosen, the SuperLotto Plus annuity is graduated.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The advertised annuity jackpot represents a 30-payment graduated annuity stream, with the graduated payments beginning at 1.51% of the jackpot amount and rise exponentially such that the final payout is 6.20% (more than quadruple that of the first payment) of the advertised jackpot amount.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Prior to 2013, the first payment was 2.5% of the annuity value (or share) of the jackpot, with the second installment 2.7%.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The remaining 24 payments increased by 0.1 percentage point yearly, so that the final (26th) installment represented 5.1% of the annuity.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Hot Spot is a quick-draw keno style game.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The game was updated on August 1, 2011, to allow players to choose to play any number of "spots" from 1 through 10 from a pool of numbers from 01 through 80.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A new higher top prize of $100,000 was also offered for 10 spot play.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Previously, players could only choose to play 2, 3, 4, 5 or 8 spots.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In addition, players can choose a Bulls-Eye wager for each draw, hoping to hit the 1 number out of the 20 numbers drawn that is selected as the bulls-eye number.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Drawings occur every day and every four minutes from 6:00 am until 2:00 am.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Lottery retailers have monitors that display Hot Spot drawings and recent results from other Lottery games.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] To meet the pari-mutuel requirements, a continuous "wagered prize fund" is created from 63% of gross sales, which ensures that the fixed payouts are met under normal circumstances, and calls for reductions should an unusually large number of individuals win a particular prize.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] If the wagered prize fund exceeds $2.9 million, prize augmentation and promotions are created to distribute the excess funds.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Arnold Schwarzenegger, as part of his redesign of California government, suggested that California join a multi-jurisdictional lottery.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In June 2005, the Lottery Commission voted to join Mega Millions.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California is unique among the 45 Mega Millions participants in that all nine prize levels for Mega Millions within its borders are always parimutuel, rather than each non-jackpot prize having a set value.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] This leads to different prize amounts for equivalent winners sold in California when compared to those sold in the other 44 jurisdictions.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] For example, the "advertised" second prize in Mega Millions is $1,000,000; but in California the record amount was set for a $3.9 million sold in Hacienda Heights in 2023 as part of the roll for a $1.1 billion jackpot.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The second prize pool within California frequently rolls; it is, in effect, a "secondary jackpot".
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Unlike the other Mega Millions members, California currently does not offer the *Megaplier*, which is drawn in Texas by a random number generator.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In February 2012, as a response to declining sales and low per-capita revenue from the lottery, California Lottery management initiated a review of whether Powerball would be appropriate for the state.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In September 2012, the Lottery Commission approved management's request to launch Powerball in April 2013, citing a net increase in revenue of $90 to $120 million as a result of Powerball, desiring to avoid the launch of a $20 scratcher in fall 2013.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] In November 2012, California promulgated the regulations for Powerball in the state.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Similar to Mega Millions, all non jackpot draws in the state are within an intrastate pool, with California sending its jackpot share (30% of draw sales) to MUSL for addition to the multi-state jackpot pool.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Each pool for a particular prize category will rollover, thus the "pick 5" prize will create a secondary jackpot similar to the "pick 5" payout in California's implementation of Mega Millions.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The record amount was set in 2023 for $3,987,429, as part of a $600 million jackpot roll.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Also, as a result of the California Supreme Court ruling which mandates pari-mutuel payouts, California will not participate in the *PowerPlay* multiplier option.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California launched Powerball on April 8, 2013, with the first drawing on April 10, 2013.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The California Lottery offered two raffles; March 17, 2007 and one on January 1, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The raffles offered the best chance to win a $1 million prize, as well as various smaller prizes, and were designed to respond to lottery players' complaints that many million dollar prizes be offered instead of a few larger prizes.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] However, the raffles did not sell out, and were not repeated.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The California Lottery has had two TV game shows.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Players qualified for the *Make Me a Millionaire* show by winning in the "Make Me a Millionaire" Scratchers game, or by a Fantasy 5 second-chance drawing; when the show began, winners from "Big Spin" Scratchers also qualified.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] After the TV show was canceled, winners of the "Make Me a Millionaire" Scratchers games, which were sold until June 25, 2010, had until December 22, 2010, to claim their opportunities to play and win prizes off the air.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Similarly, Fantasy 5 second-chance draw coupons, which were discontinued on July 4, 2010, could be submitted by December 31, 2010.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Five unaired episodes of *Make Me A Millionaire* were produced and made available for viewing on the Lottery's YouTube channel.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] During the game play, each of the 12 contestants won at least $2,000; seven of the contestants were selected randomly to play four different games of chance with a top prize of at least $1 million.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The first game, Lucky Penny, gave three players a minimum prize of $2,000 and the possibility of winning a car.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The second game is Safe Cracker, in which two players competed for prizes ranging from $2,000 to $92,000.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Next is California Cool, with one player and prizes ranging from $5,000 to $200,000.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The last game is Millionaire, also for one player; it guaranteed $10,000 with a jackpot that began at $1 million, increasing by $200,000 each week until won.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California sells scratch cards under the branding "Scratchers".
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The prizes are smaller than other lottery games, but there are better odds (averaging 1:5).
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] There are dozens of Scratchers games on sale at any time, and the selection of games changes frequently.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Winners must be claimed within 180 days of the announced end-of-game date.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Scratchers range in price from $1 to $30.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] A $20 scratcher, "$5 Million Jackpot", was introduced September 25, 2013.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] To commemorate the Lottery's 30th anniversary, on August 24, 2015, a $30 Scratcher "California Lottery 30th Anniversary" was launched.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] For each prize of less than $600, players may collect from either a Lottery retailer or the Lottery itself.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Prizes of $600 or more must be collected from the Lottery, via claim form.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Almost all prizes must be claimed within 180 days of the draw or the announced end of the game.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] If the 180th day is a weekend or holiday, the final claim date is extended to the next business day.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Any unclaimed prize money is transferred to the education fund in addition to the minimum 34% that the Lottery is already obligated to transfer from income.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Because many of the 44 Mega Millions participants have a one-year claim period, the California legislature changed the language in the Lottery Act.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Arnold Schwarzenegger signed Assembly Member Van Tran's Assembly Bill 1251, modifying California Government Code section 8880.321 to allow for a one-year claim period for a Mega Millions jackpot prize.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] This is the only prize in California that has a one-year claim period.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] All other prizes have the 180-day claim period.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] This legislation affected Mega Millions drawings after July 5, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] All prizes for Fantasy 5, Daily Derby, Daily 3, Daily 4, and non-jackpot SuperLotto Plus, Mega Millions, and Powerball prizes, are paid out in one payment, less 24% or 33% (depending upon the winner's tax documentation) Federal withholding if the prize is over $5,000.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Merchandise prizes over $5,000 are subject to 33% Federal withholding.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Scratchers tickets are generally one-payment prizes; however, some games have annuity options for payments each year, or per week.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California does not tax California Lottery winnings, however it taxes lottery winnings from other jurisdictions.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] For SuperLotto Plus and Mega Millions jackpots, the player may choose a single cash payout for a floating percentage of the jackpot, or an annuity.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] The SuperLotto Plus, Mega Millions, and Powerball payment schedule are on a graduated basis over 30 annual payments.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Until 2005, when California joined Mega Millions, the payment choice on SuperLotto Plus had to be made when the ticket was bought.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Since then, there is a 60-day window after winning, in which the choice of cash or annuity is to be made.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Unclaimed prizes remaining after the claim period expires always go to supporting California's public schools.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] As of the end of FY 2013–14, a total of $793.5 million in unclaimed prizes have been awarded to education.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] California Lottery Drawings aired at each local station.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] Galbreath's book also cited an investigation by the California State Auditor which exposed millions of additional public money misspent by the California Lottery.
[src:ferret-legging/california-state-lottery] To date none of the owed money has been repaid to education.
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] Canoe's head office is in Toronto at 333 King Street East.
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] At launch, Canoe was a joint venture between Sun Media (Toronto Sun Publishing Corp.) and Rogers Communications (Rogers Multi-Media Inc.); however, Rogers sold its shares of Canoe to BCE Inc. within its first year.
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] At the height of its popularity, Canoe had both English and French language version and owned a significant number of websites, including JAM! and the Sun Media newspaper sites.
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] According to May 2008 data from comScore Media Metrix, Canoe's portals and services receive over 7.7 million unique visitors per month in Canada, including over 3.2 million in Quebec.
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] Canoe offers the Canoe, La Toile du Québec (toile.com - defunct) and Argent (argent.canoe.ca or .com - defunct) portals, as well as the TVA and LCN websites.(tva.canoe.com and lcn.canoe.com) Canoe offers online services related to employment (jobboom.com).
[src:ferret-legging/canadian-online-explorer] Canoe has offered online services that have since gone defunct, abandoned or usurped.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] A **certified first responder** is a person who has completed a course and received certification in providing pre-hospital care for medical emergencies.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Certified individuals should have received much more instruction than someone who is trained in basic first aid and cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) but they are not necessarily a substitute for more advanced emergency medical care rendered by emergency medical technicians and paramedics.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] First responders typically provide advanced first aid level care, CPR, and automated external defibrillator (AED) usage.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Many police officers and firefighters are required to receive training as certified first responders.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Advanced medical care is typically provided by EMS, although some police officers and firefighters also train to become emergency medical technicians or paramedics.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Also called an **Emergency Medical Responder**, **Emergency First Responder**, **Medical First Responder**, or **First Responder**.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Many options are available in order to become a certified First Responder in Canada.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Courses are offered by many sources including the Canadian Red Cross, and St.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] John Ambulance, and the Department of National Defence.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Certified First Responder courses in Canada are separated into either "First Responder" or "Emergency Medical Responder" level courses.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] "Emergency Medical Responder" level courses meet the Paramedic Association of Canada's National Occupational Competency Profile, and those who receive certification at this level can work for Emergency Medical Services in some provinces.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] While all Certified First Responders in Canada are covered under Good Samaritan laws in jurisdictions where they are enacted, in some cases they have a Duty To Act for example, Ontario.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Certified First Responders who are providing medical coverage to events (such as Red Cross, St.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] John Ambulance's Patient Care Divisions and private event medical companies), as well as those who are employed by Volunteer Fire Departments, Campus Response Teams, and others who are required to perform Emergency Medical Response as part of their duties all have a Duty to Act.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] As with all medically trained and certified persons, Certified First Responders are immune to successful prosecution if assistance was given in good faith up to, and not beyond, the limits of certification and training.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The intermediate scale, the firefighter nurse (*infirmier sapeur-pompier*, ISP), is only a recent evolution and is performed by nurses who have been specially trained acting with emergency protocols; these nurses are the French equivalent of paramedics.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The arrival of first responders is thus the most common result of an emergency call.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] In addition, in France there exists a network of first responder associations, as French Red Cross (Croix-rouge française), French Civil Protection (*Protection civile*), FFSS (*Fédération Française de Sauvetage et de Secourisme*) or others.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] These CFR volunteers are allowed to supervise massive outside meetings, student gatherings, *et cetera*.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] These volunteers have followed the same special rescuer training as firefighters (PSE 1 and PSE 2, in all 70 hours of training).
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] In the Kingdom of Thailand (Thailand) First Responder is a certification most commonly achieved by local volunteers.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] This certification is referred to as Emergency Medical Responder or EMR.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] EMRs can provide emergency care for vehicle collisions, trauma, CPR, birthing, and other emergencies.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] EMRs must maintain their certification through a foundation, club, association, or government agency.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The next level of certification in emergency response is Emergency Medical Technician Basic (EMT-B).
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Training for EMR level must be done through an approved training.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Most provincial hospitals provide training or are directly connected with teaching the training.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The National Institute for Emergency Medicine of Thailand acts as the approving body for Emergency Medical Responder certification and provides the training curriculum.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Guidelines for EMRs are published in the Emergency Medical Operation Manual for First Responder Units.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Certification only lasts for two 2 years and requires refresher training to maintain.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Rescue clubs and ambulance foundations most often serve communities with volunteers to respond to emergencies with ambulances and other rescue resources.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Most foundations and clubs request volunteers to acquire at least the Emergency Medical Responder level of training.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Most EMR level units use pickup trucks with elevated caps to respond to emergencies.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] These vehicles usually are marked with the association name and seal along with lighting and sirens.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Units at this level act as the first arriving responders, and must do much to stabilize the scene for other units, such as Advanced Life Support (ALS), to arrive.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] EMR units often transport patients to medical treatment facilities especially for basic level patients and when ALS units are unavailable.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] EMRs coordinate with firefighters, police, and other medical professionals in emergency situations.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] In the United Kingdom, most statutory NHS ambulance services deploy paid first responders who drive dedicated rapid response vehicles.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] These are typically estate cars, MPVs or 4x4s, are liveried with high-visibility ambulance markings, and fitted with blue flashing lights and sirens.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] These vehicles are generally single-crewed, by a paramedic.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] This differs from most ambulances in the UK, which usually have two crew members.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Department of Transportation (D.O.T.) recognized a gap between the typical eight hours training required for providing advanced first aid (as taught by the Red Cross) and the 180 hours typical of an EMT-Basic program.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Also, some rural communities could not afford the comprehensive training and highly experienced instructors required for a full EMT-Basic course.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The First Responder training program began in 1979 as an outgrowth of the "Crash Injury Management" course.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] In 1995 the D.O.T. issued a manual for an intermediate level of training called "First Responder." This training can be completed in twenty-four to sixty hours.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Importantly, this training can be conducted by an EMT-Basic with some field experience—which is a resource available "in-house" for many volunteer fire departments who do not have the resources for full EMT training.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The first responder training is intended to fill the gap between First Aid and Emergency Medical Technician.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The American Red Cross conducts a course titled "Emergency Medical Response" that fits this definition.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] In the US the term "Emergency Medical Responder" has largely replaced the term "Certified First Responder" or "Medical First Responder" beginning in 2012.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] "Emergency Medical Responder" or "EMR" is an EMS certification level recognized by the National Registry of Emergency Medical Technicians.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] By 2015, most states recognize the level of Emergency Medical Responder.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] First Responders in the US can either provide initial emergency care first on the scene (police/fire department/search and rescue) or support Emergency Medical Technicians and Paramedics.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] They are also trained in packaging, moving and transporting patients.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] First Responders can serve as secondary providers with some volunteer EMS services.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] An Emergency Medical Responder can be seen either as an advanced first aid provider, or as a limited provider of emergency medical care when more advanced providers have not yet arrived or are not available.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Skillwise, a certified first responder in the US is often trained and allowed to do most of what an emergency medical technician is allowed to.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Some exceptions in some jurisdictions include insertion of King airways or combi-tubes, traction splinting, and administration of nebulized albuterol.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The National Fire Protection Association standards 1006 and 1670 state that all "rescuers" must have medical training to perform any technical rescue operation, including cutting the vehicle itself during an extrication.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The first responder training is considered a bare minimum for emergency service workers who may be sent out in response to an emergency call.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] It is almost always required for professional and volunteer firefighters.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] For example, all firefighters of the New York City Fire Department require a valid CFR-D (Certified First Responder - Defibrillation) certification.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] The first responder level of emergency medical training is also often required for police officers, rescue squad personnel, and search and rescue personnel.
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Many first responders have location specific training such as water rescue or mountain rescue and must take advanced courses to be certified (i.e. lifeguard).
[src:ferret-legging/certified-first-responder] Many people who do not fall into the earlier mentioned categories seek out or receive this type of training because they are likely to be first on the scene of a medical emergency, or because they work far from medical help.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The ***Chicago Tribune*** is an American daily newspaper based in Chicago, Illinois, United States.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Founded in 1847, it was formerly self-styled as the "World's Greatest Newspaper", a slogan from which its once-integrated WGN radio and WGN television received their call letters.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] It is the most-read daily newspaper in the Chicago metropolitan area and the Great Lakes region, and the sixth-largest newspaper by print circulation in the United States.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the 1850s, under Joseph Medill, the *Chicago Tribune* became closely associated with the Illinois politician Abraham Lincoln, and the then new Republican Party's progressive wing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the 20th century, under Medill's grandson 'Colonel' Robert R.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] McCormick, its reputation was that of a crusading newspaper with an outlook that promoted American conservatism and opposed Franklin D.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Its reporting and commentary reached markets outside Chicago through family and corporate relationships at the New York *Daily News* and the *Washington Times-Herald*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Through much of the 20th century and into the early 21st, it employed a network of overseas news bureaus and foreign correspondents.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the 1960s, its corporate parent owner, Tribune Company, began expanding into new markets by buying additional daily papers.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2008, for the first time in its history, its editorial page endorsed a Democrat, Barack Obama, a U.S. senator from Illinois, for U.S. president.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Originally published solely as a broadsheet, the *Tribune* announced on January 13, 2009, that it would continue publishing as a broadsheet for home delivery, but it would publish in tabloid format for newsstand, news box, and commuter station sales.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The change, however, proved unpopular with readers; in August 2011, the *Tribune* discontinued the tabloid edition, returning to its established broadsheet format through all distribution channels.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* was owned by parent company Tribune Publishing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In May 2021, Tribune Publishing was acquired by Alden Global Capital, which operates its media properties through Digital First Media; since then, the newspaper's coverage has evolved away from national and international news and toward coverage of Illinois and especially Chicago-area news.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* settled a lawsuit over illegal charges to consumers in 2013 and was sued again for deceptive billing practices in 2023.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* was founded by James Kelly, John E.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Forrest, publishing the first edition on June 10, 1847.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Numerous changes in ownership and editorship took place over the next eight years.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Initially, the *Tribune* was not politically affiliated, but it tended to support either the Whig or Free Soil parties against the Democrats in elections.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] By late 1853, it was frequently running editorials that criticized foreigners and Roman Catholics.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] About this time, it also became a strong proponent of the temperance movement.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] However nativist its editorials may have been, it was not until February 10, 1855, that the *Tribune* formally affiliated itself with the nativist American or Know Nothing party, whose candidate Levi Boone was elected Mayor of Chicago the following month.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Webster, later General Webster and chief of staff at the Battle of Shiloh, and Charles H.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Ray of Galena, Illinois, through Horace Greeley, convinced Joseph Medill of Cleveland's *Leader* to become managing editor.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Ray became editor-in-chief, Medill became the managing editor, and Alfred Cowles, Sr., brother of Edwin Cowles, initially was the bookkeeper.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Each purchased one third of the *Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Under their leadership, the *Tribune* distanced itself from the Know Nothings, and became the main Chicago organ of the Republican Party.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] However, the paper continued to print anti-Catholic and anti-Irish editorials, in the wake of the massive famine immigration from Ireland.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* absorbed three other Chicago publications under the new editors: the *Free West* in 1855, the *Democratic Press* of William Bross in 1858, and the *Chicago Democrat* in 1861, whose editor, John Wentworth, left his position when elected as Mayor of Chicago.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Between 1858 and 1860, the paper was known as the *Chicago Press & Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On October 25, 1860, it became the *Chicago Daily Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Before and during the American Civil War, the new editors strongly supported Abraham Lincoln, whom Medill helped secure the presidency in 1860, and pushed an abolitionist agenda.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper remained a force in Republican politics for years afterwards.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1861, the *Tribune* published new lyrics by William W.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Patton for the song "John Brown's Body".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] These rivaled the lyrics published two months later by Julia Ward Howe.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Medill served as mayor of Chicago for one term after the Great Chicago Fire of 1871.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the 20th century, under Colonel Robert R.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] McCormick, who took control in the 1920s, the paper was strongly isolationist and aligned with the Old Right in its coverage of political news and social trends.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] It used the motto "The American Paper for Americans".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] From the 1930s to the 1950s, it excoriated the Democrats and the New Deal of Franklin D.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Roosevelt, was resolutely disdainful of the British, and expressed support for Chiang Kai-shek and Sen.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] When McCormick assumed the position of co-editor with his cousin Joseph Medill Patterson in 1910, the *Tribune* was the third-best-selling paper among Chicago's eight dailies, with a circulation of only 188,000.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The young cousins added features such as advice columns and homegrown comic strips, such as *Little Orphan Annie* and *Moon Mullins*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] They promoted political crusades, and their first success came with the ouster of the Republican political boss of Illinois, Sen.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] At the same time, the *Tribune* competed with the Hearst paper, the *Chicago Examiner*, in a circulation war.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] By 1914, the cousins succeeded in forcing out James Keeley, the newspaper's managing editor.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] By 1918, the *Examiner* was forced to merge with the *Chicago Herald*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1919, Patterson left the *Tribune* and moved to New York City to launch his own newspaper, the *New York Daily News*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In a renewed circulation war with Hearst's *Herald-Examiner*, McCormick and Hearst ran rival lotteries in 1922.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won the battle, adding 250,000 readers to its ranks.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The same year, the *Chicago Tribune* hosted an international design competition for its new headquarters, the Tribune Tower, offering a $50,000 prize for first place.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The competition worked brilliantly as a publicity stunt, and more than 260 entries were received.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The winner was a neo-Gothic design by New York architects John Mead Howells and Raymond Hood.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Construction of the Tribune Tower was completed in 1925.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The newspaper sponsored a pioneering attempt at Arctic aviation in 1929, a proposed round-trip to Europe across Greenland and Iceland in a Sikorsky amphibious aircraft.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] However, the aircraft was destroyed by ice on July 15, 1929, near Ungava Bay at the tip of Labrador, Canada.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The crew were rescued by the Canadian science ship CSS *Acadia*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s reputation for innovation extended to radio.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] It bought an early station, WDAP, in 1924 and renamed it WGN, the station call letters standing for the paper's self-description as the "World's Greatest Newspaper".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] WGN Television was launched on April 5, 1948.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] These broadcast stations remained *Tribune* properties for nine decades and were among the oldest newspaper/broadcasting cross-ownerships in the country.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s legendary sports editor Arch Ward created the Major League Baseball All-Star Game in 1933 as part of the city's Century of Progress exposition.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] One of the great scoops in *Tribune* history came when it obtained the text of the Treaty of Versailles in June 1919.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Another was its revelation of United States war plans on the eve of the Pearl Harbor attack.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune*'s June 7, 1942, front-page article implying that the United States had broken Japan's naval code could have resulted in the Japanese learning a closely guarded military secret.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The story implying that Americans broke the enemy naval codes was not cleared by censors, and had U.S.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Roosevelt so enraged that he considered shutting down the *Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] From 1940 to 1943, the paper supplemented its comic strip offerings with *The Chicago Tribune Comic Book*, responding to the new success of comic books.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] At the same time, it launched the more successful and longer-lasting *The Spirit Section*, which was also an attempt by newspapers to compete with the new medium.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Under McCormick's stewardship, the *Tribune* was a champion of modified spelling for simplicity.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Beginning in 1934, the paper compiled lists of dozens of common words whose spelling could be made "saner", removing double L's and shortening "-ogue" endings to "-og", among other changes.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper is known for a mistake it made during the 1948 presidential election.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] At that time, much of its composing room staff was on strike.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Early returns led editors to believe (along with many in the country) that the Republican candidate Thomas Dewey would win.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] An early edition of the next day's paper carried the headline "Dewey Defeats Truman", turning the paper into a collector's item.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Truman won and proudly brandished the newspaper in a famous picture taken at St.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Beneath the headline was a false article, written by Arthur Sears Henning, which purported to describe West Coast results although written before East Coast election returns were available.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] McCormick, a vigorous campaigner for the Republican Party, died in 1955, just four days before Democratic boss Richard J.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Daley was elected mayor for the first time.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1969, under the leadership of publisher Harold Grumhaus and editor Clayton Kirkpatrick, the *Tribune* began reporting from a wider viewpoint.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper retained its Republican and conservative perspective in its editorials, but it began to publish perspectives in wider commentary that represented a spectrum of diverse opinions, while its news reporting no longer had the conservative slant it had in the McCormick years.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In January 1974, *Time* magazine named the *Tribune* on its "Ten Best American Dailies" list for its local investigative reporting under George Bliss as well as its "calmer tone and a less polemical approach to events" brought on by Kirkpatrick.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On May 1, 1974, in a major feat of journalism, the *Tribune* published the complete 246,000-word text of the Watergate tapes, in a 44-page supplement that hit the streets 24 hours after the transcripts' release by the Nixon White House.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Not only was the *Tribune* the first newspaper to publish the transcripts, but it beat the U.S.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Government Printing Office's published version, and made headlines doing so.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Nixon has upheld the standards and dignity of the Presidency," and called for Nixon's resignation.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* call for Nixon to resign made news, reflecting not only the change in the type of conservatism practiced by the paper, but as a watershed event in terms of Nixon's hopes for survival in office.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The White House reportedly perceived the *Tribune*'s editorial as a loss of a longtime supporter and as a blow to Nixon's hopes to weather the scandal.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On December 7, 1975, Kirkpatrick announced in a column on the editorial page that Rick Soll, a "young and talented columnist" for the paper, whose work had "won a following among many *Tribune* readers over the last two years", had resigned from the paper.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He had acknowledged that one column he wrote, dating to November 23, 1975, contained verbatim passages written by another columnist in 1967 and later published in a collection.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick did not identify the columnist.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The passages in question, Kirkpatrick wrote, were from a notebook where Soll regularly entered words, phrases and bits of conversation which he had wished to remember.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper initially suspended Soll for a month without pay.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick wrote that further evidence was revealed came out that another of Soll's columns contained information which he knew was false.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] At that point, *Tribune* editors decided to accept the resignation offered by Soll when the internal investigation began.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] After leaving, Soll married Pam Zekman, a Chicago newspaper (and future TV) reporter.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He worked for the short-lived *Chicago Times* magazine, by Small Newspaper Group Inc. of Kankakee, Illinois, in the late 1980s.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Soll was born in 1946, in Chicago, to Marjorie and Jules Soll.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Soll graduated from New Trier High School, received a Bachelor of Arts in 1968 from Colgate University, and a master's degree from Medill School of Journalism, Northwestern University in 1970.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In January 1977, *Tribune* columnist Will Leonard died at age 64.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In March 1978, the *Tribune* announced that it hired columnist Bob Greene from the *Chicago Sun-Times*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Kirkpatrick stepped down as editor in 1979 and was succeeded by Maxwell McCrohon, who served as editor until 1981.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He was transitioned to a corporate position.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] McCrohon held the corporate position until 1983, when he left to become editor-in-chief of the United Press International.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] James Squires served as the paper's editor from July 1981 until December 1989.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Jack Fuller served as the *Tribune*'s editor from 1989 until 1993, when he became the president and chief executive officer of the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Howard Tyner served as the *Tribune*'s editor from 1993 until 2001, when he was promoted to vice president/editorial for Tribune Publishing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won 11 Pulitzer prizes during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Editorial cartoonist Dick Locher won the award in 1983, and editorial cartoonist Jeff MacNelly won one in 1985.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Then, future editor Jack Fuller won a Pulitzer for editorial writing in 1986.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1987, reporters Jeff Lyon and Peter Gorner won a Pulitzer for explanatory reporting, and in 1988, Dean Baquet, William Gaines and Ann Marie Lipinski won a Pulitzer for investigative reporting.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1989, Lois Wille won a Pulitzer for editorial writing and Clarence Page snagged the award for commentary.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1994, Ron Kotulak won a Pulitzer for explanatory journalism, while R.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Bruce Dold won it for editorial writing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1998, reporter Paul Salopek won a Pulitzer for explanatory writing, and in 1999, architecture critic Blair Kamin won it for criticism.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In September 1981, baseball writer Jerome Holtzman was hired by the *Tribune* after a 38-year career at the *Sun-Times*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In September 1982, the *Chicago Tribune* opened a new $180 million printing facility, Freedom Center.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In November 1982, *Tribune* managing editor William H.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "Bill" Jones, who had won a Pulitzer Prize in 1971, died at age 43 of cardiac arrest as a result of complications from a long battle with leukemia.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In May 1983, *Tribune* columnist Aaron Gold died at age 45 of complications from leukemia.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Gold had coauthored the Tribune's "Inc." column with Michael Sneed and prior to that had written the paper's "Tower Ticker" column.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* scored a coup in 1984 when it hired popular columnist Mike Royko away from the rival *Sun-Times*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "He has done a great job for us," editor James Squires said at the time.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "It's a question of how much a person can do physically.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] We think you need to be a newspaper person first, and Gene Siskel has always tried to do that.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] But there comes a point when a career is so big that you can't do that." Siskel declined to comment on the new arrangement, but Ebert publicly criticized Siskel's *Tribune* bosses for punishing Siskel for taking their television program to a company other than Tribune Entertainment.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Siskel remained in that freelance position until he died in 1999.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He was replaced as film critic by Dave Kehr.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In August 1988, *Chicago Tribune* reporter Michael Coakley died at age 41 of complications from AIDS.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In November 1992, *Tribune* associate subject editor Searle "Ed" Hawley was arrested by Chicago police and charged with seven counts of aggravated criminal sexual abuse for allegedly having sex with three juveniles in his home in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Hawley formally resigned from the paper in early 1993, and pleaded guilty in April 1993.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In October 1993, the *Tribune* fired its longtime military affairs writer, retired Marine David Evans, saying publicly that the position was being replaced by a national security writer.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In December 1993, the *Tribune*'s longtime Washington, D.C. bureau chief, Nicholas Horrock, was fired after he chose not to attend a meeting that editor Howard Tyner requested of him in Chicago.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Horrock, who shortly thereafter left the paper, was replaced by James Warren, who attracted new attention to the *Tribune*'s D.C. bureau through his continued attacks on celebrity broadcast journalists in Washington.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In December 1993, the *Tribune* hired Margaret Holt from the *South Florida Sun-Sentinel* as its assistant managing editor for sports, making her the first female to head a sports department at any of the nation's 10 largest newspapers.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In mid-1995, Holt was replaced as sports editor by Tim Franklin and shifted to a newly created job, customer service editor.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1994, reporter Brenda You was fired by the *Tribune* after free-lancing for supermarket tabloid newspapers and lending them photographs from the *Tribune*'s photo library.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] She later worked for the *National Enquirer* and as a producer for *The Jerry Springer Show* before committing suicide in November 2005.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In April 1994, the *Tribune*'s new television critic, Ken Parish Perkins, wrote an article about then-WFLD morning news anchor Bob Sirott in which Perkins quoted Sirott as making a statement that Sirott later denied making.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Sirott criticized Perkins on the air, and the *Tribune* later printed a correction acknowledging that Sirott had never made that statement.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Eight months later, Perkins stepped down as TV critic, and he left the paper shortly thereafter.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The program brought young journalists in and out of the paper for one-year stints, seldom resulting in a full-time job.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Hill, who wrote for the paper from 1992 until 1993, acknowledged to the *Chicago Reader* that she had written the diatribe originally for the Internet, and that the piece eventually was edited for *Newcity*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1997, the *Tribune* celebrated its 150th anniversary in part by tapping longtime reporter Stevenson Swanson to edit the book *Chicago Days: 150 Defining Moments in the Life of a Great City*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On April 29, 1997, popular columnist Mike Royko died of a brain aneurysm.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On September 2, 1997, the *Tribune* promoted longtime City Hall reporter John Kass to take Royko's place as the paper's principal Page Two news columnist.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On June 1, 1997, the *Tribune* published what ended up becoming a very popular column by Mary Schmich called "Advice, like youth, probably just wasted on the young", otherwise known as "Wear Sunscreen" or the "Sunscreen Speech".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The most popular and well-known form of the essay is the successful music single released in 1999, accredited to Baz Luhrmann.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1998, reporter Jerry Thomas was fired by the *Tribune* after he wrote a cover article on boxing promoter Don King for *Emerge* magazine at the same time that he was writing a cover article on King for the *Chicago Tribune* Sunday magazine.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper decided to fire Thomas—and suspend his photographer on the *Emerge* story, Pulitzer Prize-winning *Tribune* photographer Ovie Carter for a month—because Thomas did not tell the *Tribune* about his outside work and also because the *Emerge* story wound up appearing in print first.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has been a leader on the Internet, acquiring 10 percent of America Online in the early 1990s, then launching such web sites as Chicagotribune.com (1995), Metromix.com (1996), **ChicagoSports.com** (1999), **ChicagoBreakingNews.com** (2008), and ChicagoNow (2009).
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2002, the paper launched a tabloid edition targeted at 18- to 34-year-olds known as *RedEye*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Ann Marie Lipinski was the paper's editor from February 2001 until stepping down on July 17, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Kern was named the paper's editor in July 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In early August 2008, managing editor for news Hanke Gratteau resigned, and several weeks later, managing editor for features James Warren resigned as well.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Both were replaced by Jane Hirt, who previously had been the editor of the *Tribune*'s *RedEye* tabloid.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In June 2000, Times Mirror merged with Tribune Company making *The Baltimore Sun* and its community papers Baltimore Sun Media Group / Patuxent Publishing a subsidiary of Tribune.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In July 2000, Tribune outdoors columnist John Husar, who had written about his need for a new liver transplant, died at age 63, just over a week after receiving part of a new liver from a live donor.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Howard County Times* was named 2010 Newspaper of the Year by the Suburban Newspaper Association.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Towson Times* expands coverage beyond the Towson area and includes Baltimore County government and politics.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won five Pulitzer prizes in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2003, editorial writer Cornelia Grumman snagged the award for editorial writing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2005, Julia Keller won a Pulitzer for feature reporting on a tornado that struck Utica, Illinois.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] And, in 2008, an investigative reporting team including Patricia Callahan, Maurice Possley, Sam Roe, Ted Gregory, Michael Oneal, Evan Osnos and photojournalist Scott Strazzante won the Pulitzer for its series about faulty government regulation of defective toys, cribs and car seats.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In late 2001, sports columnist Michael Holley announced he was leaving the *Tribune* after just two months because he was homesick.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He ultimately returned to *The Boston Globe*, where he had been working immediately before the *Tribune* had hired him.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "Greene's behavior was a serious violation of *Tribune* ethics and standards for its journalists," Lipinski wrote.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In January 2003, Mike Downey, formerly of the *Los Angeles Times*, was hired as new *Tribune* sports columnist.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] He and colleague Rick Morrissey would write the *In the Wake of the News Column* originated by Ring Lardner.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In March 2004, the *Tribune* announced that freelance reporter Uli Schmetzer, who retired from the *Tribune* in 2002 after 16 years as a foreign correspondent, had fabricated the name and occupation of a person he had quoted in a story.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper terminated Schmetzer as a contract reporter and began a review of the 300 stories that Schmetzer had written over the prior three years.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "Upon questioning, the freelance writer indicated the column was based on an amalgam of three restaurants and could not verify the prices," the paper noted.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] After the correction, the *Tribune* stopped using Falanga.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In October 2004, *Tribune* editor Ann Marie Lipinski at the last minute spiked a story written for the paper's WomanNews section by freelance reporter Lisa Bertagnoli titled "You c_nt say that (or can you?)," about a noted vulgarism.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper ordered every spare body to go to the *Tribune*'s printing plant to pull already-printed WomanNews sections containing the story from the October 27 package of preprinted sections in the *Tribune*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In September 2008, the *Tribune* considered hiring controversial sports columnist Jay Mariotti, shortly after his abrupt resignation from *Tribune* archrival *Chicago Sun-Times*.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Discussions ultimately ended, however, after the *Sun-Times* threatened to sue for violating Mariotti's noncompete agreement, which was to run until August 2009.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Sports columnist Rick Morrissey defected to the *Sun-Times* in December 2009.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Reporters declined to speak on the record to the Associated Press about their issues.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] "We'll let the e-mail speak for itself," reporter John Chase told the AP.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the wake of the controversy, Kern abruptly discontinued the effort, which he described as "a brief market research project".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* broke the story on May 29, 2009, that several students had been admitted to the University of Illinois based upon connections or recommendations by the school's Board of Trustees, Chicago politicians, and members of the Rod Blagojevich administration.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Initially denying the existence of a so-called "Category I" admissions program, university President B.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Joseph "Joe" White and Chancellor Richard Herman later admitted that there were instances of preferential treatment.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Although they claimed the list was short and their role was minor, the *Tribune*, in particular, revealed emails through a FOIA finding that White had received a recommendation for a relative of convicted fundraiser Tony Rezko to be admitted.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The Tribune also later posted emails from Herman pushing for underqualified students to be accepted.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has since filed suit against the university administration under the Freedom of Information Act to acquire the names of students benefited by administrative clout and impropriety.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On February 8, 2010, the *Chicago Tribune* shrank its newspaper's width by an inch.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] They said that the new format was becoming the industry standard and that there would be minimal content changes.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In July 2011, the *Chicago Tribune* underwent its first round of layoffs of editorial employees in more than two years, letting go about 20 editors and reporters.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Among those let go were DuPage County reporter Art Barnum, Editorial Board member Pat Widder and photographer Dave Pierini.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On March 15, 2012, the *Tribune* laid off 15 editorial staffers, including security guard Wendell Smothers (Smothers then died on November 12, 2012).
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] At the same time, the paper gave buyouts to six editorial staffers, including Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter William Mullen, Barbara Mahany and Nancy Reese.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In June 2012, the *Tribune*'s Pulitzer Prize-winning cultural critic Julia Keller left the paper to join the faculty of Ohio University and to pursue a career as a novelist.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In October 2012, the *Tribune*'s science and medicine reporter, Trine Tsouderos, quit to join a public relations firm.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Also in October 2012, the *Tribune* announced plans to create a paywall for its website, offering digital-only subscriptions at $14.99 per month, starting on November 1, 2012.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Seven-day print subscribers would continue to have unlimited online access at no additional charge.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In February 2013, the *Tribune* agreed to pay a total of $660,000 to settle a class-action lawsuit that had been filed against the paper by 46 current and former reporters of its TribLocal local-news reporting group over unpaid overtime wages.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The suit had been filed in federal court on behalf of Carolyn Rusin, who had been a TribLocal staff reporter from July 2010 until October 2011.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The paper's TribLocal unit had been formed in 2007 and uses staff reporters, freelance writers and user-generated content to produce hyperlocal Chicago-area community news.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On June 12, 2013, the Boston Marathon bombing tribute was posted again, which showed the words "We are Chicago" above the names of Boston sports teams.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On the graphic on June 12, the word "Bruins" was ripped off and the comment was added, "Yeah, not right now we're not", in a reference to the 2013 Stanley Cup Finals, which play the Chicago Blackhawks against the Boston Bruins.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Gerould Kern tweeted later that the *Tribune* "still supports [Boston] after all you've been through.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On November 20, 2013, the *Tribune* laid off another 12 or so editorial staffers.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On April 6, 2014, the *Tribune* increased the newsstand price of its Sunday/Thanksgiving Day paper by 50 percent to $2.99 for a single copy.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] By January 2017 the price increased again, up $1 or 40% at newsracks, to $3.50.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On January 28, 2015, metropolitan editor Peter Kendall was named managing editor, replacing Jane Hirt, who had resigned several months earlier.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Colin McMahon was named associate editor.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On February 18, 2016, the Tribune announced the retirement of editor Gerould Kern and the immediate promotion of the paper's editorial page editor, R.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On June 9, 2018, the Tribune ended their 93-year stint at Tribune Tower and moved to One Prudential Plaza.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The tower was later converted to condos.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On February 27, 2020, the *Tribune* announced that publisher and editor Bruce Dold would leave the *Tribune* on April 30, 2020, and would step down immediately as editor in chief.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] His replacement as editor was Colin McMahon.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Also, the paper announced that one of the two managing editors of the paper, Peter Kendall, would leave the *Tribune* on February 28, 2020.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In January 2021, the *Chicago Tribune* moved out of One Prudential Plaza, and relocated their offices and newsroom to Freedom Center.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In May 2021, the paper was purchased by Alden Global Capital.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Alden immediately launched a round of employee buyouts, reducing the newsroom staff by 25 percent, and the cuts continued.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] A former reporter said the paper is being "snuffed out, quarter after quarter after quarter".
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Mitch Pugh was named the *Tribune*'s executive editor on August 20, 2021, after eight years in the same role at *The Post and Courier* in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has remained economically conservative, being widely skeptical of increasing the minimum wage and entitlement spending.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2018, the *Chicago Tribune* and *Los Angeles Times* withdrew their websites from European Union nations to avoid the purview of the General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2004, the *Tribune* endorsed President George W.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Bush for reelection, a decision consistent with its longstanding support for the Republican Party.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2008, it endorsed Democratic candidate and Illinois junior U.S.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Senator Barack Obama—the first time that it had ever endorsed a Democrat for president.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* endorsed Obama once again for reelection in 2012, and in 2020 would endorse another Democrat, Joe Biden, who had served as vice president under Obama.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* has occasionally backed candidates of other parties for president.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 1872, it supported Horace Greeley, a former Republican Party newspaper editor, and in 1912 the paper endorsed Theodore Roosevelt, who ran on the Progressive Party slate against Republican President William Howard Taft.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2016, the Tribune endorsed the Libertarian Party candidate, former New Mexico Governor Gary Johnson, for president, over Republican Donald Trump and Democrat Hillary Clinton.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Even when it uniformly backed Republicans for president, the *Tribune* endorsed some Democrats for lesser offices, including endorsements of Bill Foster, Barack Obama for the Senate and Democrat Melissa Bean, who defeated Philip Crane, the House of Representatives' longest-serving Republican.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Although the *Tribune* endorsed George Ryan in the 1998 Illinois gubernatorial race, the paper subsequently investigated and reported on the scandals surrounding Ryan during his preceding years as Secretary of State.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Ryan declined to run for re-election in 2002 and was subsequently indicted, convicted and imprisoned as a result of the scandal.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Chicago Tribune* was the founding business unit of Tribune Company (since renamed *Tribune Media*), which included many newspapers and television stations around the country.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In Chicago, Tribune Media owned the WGN radio station (720 AM) and WGN-TV (Channel 9).
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Tribune Company also owned the *Los Angeles Times*—which displaced the Tribune as the company's largest property—and the Chicago Cubs baseball team.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The Cubs were sold in 2009;the newspapers spun off in 2014 as Tribune Publishing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Tribune Company owned the New York *Daily News* from its 1919 founding until its 1991 sale to British newspaper magnate Robert Maxwell.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Joseph Medill Patterson — was a grandson of Joseph Medill and a cousin of *Tribune* editor Robert McCormick.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Both Patterson and McCormick were enthusiasts of simplified spelling, another hallmark of their papers for many years.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In 2008, the Tribune Company sold the Long Island newspaper *Newsday*—founded in 1940 by Patterson's daughter (and Medill's great-granddaughter), Alicia Patterson—to Long Island cable TV company Cablevision.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] From 1925 to 2018, the Chicago Tribune was housed in the Tribune Tower on North Michigan Avenue on the Magnificent Mile.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The building is neo-Gothic in style, and the design was the winner of an international competition hosted by the Tribune.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The Chicago Tribune moved in June 2018 to the Prudential Plaza office complex overlooking Millennium Park after Tribune Media sold Tribune Tower to developers.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Colonel McCormick prevented the *Tribune* for years from participating in the Pulitzer Prize competition.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] But it has won 29 of the awards over the years, including many for editorial writing.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won its first post-McCormick Pulitzer in 1961, when Carey Orr won the award for editorial cartooning.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Reporter George Bliss won a Pulitzer the following year for reporting, and reporter Bill Jones another in 1971 for reporting.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] A reporting team won the award in 1973, followed by reporter William Mullen and photographer Ovie Carter, who won a Pulitzer for international reporting in 1975.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] A local reporting team won the award in 1976, and architecture critic Paul Gapp won a Pulitzer in 1979.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The *Tribune* won the Pulitzer Prize for local reporting on May 4, 2026, for its coverage of Operation Midway Blitz, the Trump administration's immigration enforcement mission in the Chicago area last fall.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In December 2007, the Tribune Company was bought out by Chicago real estate magnate Sam Zell in an $8.2 billion deal.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] A year after going private, following a $124 million third-quarter loss, the Tribune Company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on December 8, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The company made its filing with the U.S.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Bankruptcy Court for the District of Delaware, citing a debt of $13 billion and assets of $7.6 billion.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Sam Zell originally planned to turn the company into a private company through the creation of an ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) within the company, but due to poor management that existed prior to his ownership, this did not work out as well as he intended.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] As part of its bankruptcy plan, owner Sam Zell intended to sell the Cubs to reduce debt.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] This sale has become linked to the corruption charges leading to the arrest of former Illinois Governor Rod Blagojevich on December 9, 2008.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Specifically, Blagojevich was accused of exploiting the paper's financial trouble in an effort to have several editors fired.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] In the bankruptcy, unsecured bondholders of Tribune Co. essentially claimed that ordinary Tribune shareholders participated in a "fraudulent transfer" of wealth.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The law firm Brown Rudnick, representing the Aurelius group of junior creditors, filed fraudulent transfer claims and fraud claims against 33,000 to 35,000 stockholders who bought Tribune stock.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Prolonged due to these claims against former officers, directors, and every former stockholder of the Chicago Tribune Company, the Tribune's bankruptcy-related legal and professional fees of $500 million were more than twice the usual amount for that size of company.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The Tribune Co. emerged from bankruptcy in January 2013, partially owned by private equity firms which had speculated on its distressed debt.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The reorganized company's plan included selling off many of its assets.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Tribune Publishing, owning the *Chicago Tribune*, *Los Angeles Times*, and eight other newspapers, was spun off as a separate publicly traded company in August 2014.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The parent Tribune Company was renamed Tribune Media.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Tribune Publishing started life with a $350 million loan, $275 million of which was paid as a dividend to Tribune Media.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The publishing company was also due to lease its office space from Tribune Media for $30 million per year through 2017.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Spinning off Tribune Publishing avoided the capital gains taxes that would accrue from selling those assets.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The shares in Tribune Publishing were given tax-free to stakeholders in Tribune Media, the largest shareholder was Oaktree Capital Management with 18.5%.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] Tribune Media, retaining the non-newspaper broadcasting, entertainment, real estate, and other investments, also sold off some of the non-newspaper properties.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] On February 7, 2018, Tribune Publishing Company agreed to sell the *Los Angeles Times* to billionaire biotech investor Patrick Soon-Shiong.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The purchase, made through Soon-Shiong's Nant Capital investment fund, was valued at $500 million, along with the assumption of $90 million in pension liabilities.
[src:ferret-legging/chicago-tribune] The deal, which also included the *San Diego Union-Tribune* and other assets, was finalized on June 16, 2018.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In print, *Cracked* conspicuously copied *Mad*'s layouts and style, and even featured a simpleminded, wide-cheeked mascot, a janitor named Sylvester P.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Smythe on its covers, in a manner similar to *Mad*'s Alfred E.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Unlike Neuman, who appears primarily on covers, Smythe sometimes spoke and was frequently seen inside the magazine, interacting with parody subjects and other regular characters.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The magazine's first editor was Sol Brodsky, who was better known as a journeyman artist and later production manager and a publishing vice president at Marvel Comics.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Editor Terry Bisson later recalled, "The whole company was about lowball imitations.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The publisher, Robert Sproul, wanted to put out some imitations of western, romance and astrology mags, and I was hired (at about age 27) to put them together because of my romance mag experience...
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The pseudomags did pretty well (this was a very low end market)." Many of the *Cracked* contributors also worked on these titles.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] A number of monster-themed issues were printed under the *Cracked* umbrella, capitalizing on such publications as *Fangoria* and *Famous Monsters of Filmland*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Sproul published *Cracked* into the 1980s.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] However, even as the company chased publishing trends, its long-running flagship title was *Cracked Magazine*—or ***Cracked Mazagine***, as its cover often read, deliberately misspelling "magazine".
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Some notable artists provided art for *Cracked*, in particular John Severin.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Severin was one of the original artists on *Mad*, and he worked heavily on EC Comics' war books.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] He was also one of the pre-eminent artists in Western comics.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] He eventually came to be best known as *Cracked*'s house cartoonist.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] For almost 40 years, he was the magazine's mainstay artist, frequently illustrating multiple articles in the same issue and virtually all of its covers.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The magazine also regularly featured good girl artist Bill Ward, comic book stalwart Howard Nostrand, and gag cartoonists Don Orehek and Charles Rodrigues.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In later years, the magazine was a useful training ground for such future independent comic book creators as Rick Altergott, Dan Clowes, and Peter Bagge.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Clowes later discussed his childhood ambivalence for the magazine with an interviewer: "No one was ever a fan of *Cracked*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] We would buy *Mad* every month, but about two weeks later we would get anxious for new material.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] We would tell ourselves, 'OK, we are not going to buy *Cracked*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Others included Marvel Comics regulars Steve Ditko and Gene Colan.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In its later days, *Cracked* found it difficult to attract and retain the level of talent that the better-paying, better-selling *Mad* could.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Richmond, who drew four articles for *Cracked*, reported on his webpage that he was paid just $100 for a finished page, a small fraction of what he earned for his first *Mad* assignment.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Richmond also wrote about the bad feeling caused by his short tenure at *Cracked*: "[Editor Dick Kulpa] was very upset about my leaving Cracked for *Mad*, but let's be real ... not doing so would have been the same as a minor league Triple-A shortstop refusing a call up to the majors.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] That was no decision at all." Mike Snider had been submitting to both publications, and made the move to *Mad* after it accepted an article that had already been okayed by *Cracked*; Snider was obliged to rescind his submission to the lower-paying magazine.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] One publisher who looked into buying the *Cracked* operation felt that *Mad* was "in a class by itself" and that "*Cracked* couldn't top *Mad's* lineup".
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] A typical issue of *Cracked* included two TV or movie parodies illustrated by Severin.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The magazine also published "interview" articles featuring the recurring character Nanny Dickering (Nancy Dickerson was then an investigative newscaster).
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] One of the magazine's longest-running features was "Shut-Ups", which were two-panel gags in which a character would make an observation or excuse in the first panel, and then be told to "SHUT UP" in the second, as the true situation was visually revealed.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] "Hudd & Dini" by Vic Martin, a gag strip about two convicts' failed schemes to escape prison, also ran frequently, as did John Severin's Western strip "Sagebrush." Other recurring features included "Ye Hang-Ups", "The Talking Blob", "Spies vs.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Sabs" (originally "Saboteurs & Investigators") and, in the 1980s, "the Uggly Family" by Daniel Clowes.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Ace Books published four *Cracked* collections, *The Cracked Reader* (K-111 NA, 1960), *More Cracked*, *Completely Cracked* and *Cracked Again* (M-146, 1965).
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Sproul was listed as editor of the 1960 book.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Dell Publishing produced six collections; *Get Me Cracked*, *Half-Cracked*, *Cracked Up*, *Your Cracked*, *Cracked in the Saddle* and *It's a Cracked World*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In the mid-1970s, *Cracked* moved into foreign markets.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In Great Britain, they produced *Cracked British Edition*, which consisted entirely of reprinted material from the American magazine edited to localize spelling and pop-culture references.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In Germany, there were three publications that included *Cracked* reprints.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] First was *Kaputt*, which ran from 1974 to 1983; it was followed by *Stupid*, which ran from 1983 to 1984, and, finally, *Panic*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] All magazines used original material in addition to the translated *Cracked* reprints.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Articles were often colorized, particularly in *Stupid*, or printed in black and white with a single added color.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Covers were original, but were often reworkings of previous *Cracked* covers.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] It was published in Brazil under the name *Pancada* by Editora Abril, from 1977 to 1980.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The content was translated from the English original and adapted to the Brazilian reality of the time (the Democratic and Republican parties were substituted respectively by ARENA and MDB, political parties of that era), and football jokes were made into soccer jokes.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Most covers were reused from the original American magazine, but some were made by local artists.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Two attempts were made in the 1990s to launch the magazine in Australia.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In 1985, Mort Todd became editor of *Cracked* magazine at age 23.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In 1987, *Cracked* made waves in the comic industry by seemingly raiding cartoonist Don Martin from rival *Mad*, after Martin's 32-year career there.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Martin had left *Mad* months earlier due to a business dispute.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Martin worked for *Cracked* for about six years, and the magazine, in a tweak at its rival, billed him as "*Cracked*'s Crackedest Artist".
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] *Cracked*'s concurrent attempt to sign *Mad*'s caricaturist Mort Drucker was unsuccessful, but the magazine did acquire longtime *Mad* contributor Lou Silverstone as editor and writer.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Former *Mad* associate editor Jerry DeFuccio also worked at *Cracked* for a short period.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Though sales of *Cracked* always lagged far behind those of *Mad*, *Cracked* endured for more than four decades through low pay rates and overhead, and by being part of large publishing groups that could bundle *Cracked* in with its other magazines as a package arrangement for distributors.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In the 1990s, *Cracked* also benefited from the collapse of the *National Lampoon*, picking up Andy Simmons as an editor, as well as such former *Lampoon* contributors as Ron Barrett, Randy Jones, and Ed Subitzky.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In 1995, Greg Grabianski began his career as a writer and associate editor at *Cracked* before going on to write for TV and film projects including *Beavis & Butthead* and the *Scary Movie* franchise.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] At its height, *Cracked*'s circulation might have been a third of *Mad*'s, with the overall total generally rising or falling along with the bigger magazine's fortunes.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] But at its nadir in the 2000s, this sales figure plunged to around 25,000–35,000 per bi-monthly issue, or about one-eighth of *Mad*'s monthly circulation, which had also plummeted from its mid-1970s peak of over 2 million per issue.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In late 1999, *Cracked*'s then-parent company, Globe Communications (publisher of the national tabloid *The Globe*), was sold to American Media, Inc., the company that publishes the tabloids *The National Enquirer* and the *Weekly World News*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] American Media's primary interest in the deal was in acquiring its rival, *The Globe*, but *Cracked* came along as part of the transaction.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] American Media moved Globe Communications' New York City operations to Florida, where American Media was headquartered.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] As a result, *Cracked*'s offices moved to Florida as well.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Most of the magazine's long-term editors and writers did not move to Florida, leading to a large turnover in *Cracked*'s staff.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Published reports indicate that American Media never had an interest in supporting the magazine, which was only selling in the high five figures, compared with AMI's multi-million-selling line of tabloids.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] *Cracked*'s distribution under American Media grew increasingly sporadic.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In 2000, American Media sold *Cracked* to one of its former *Weekly World News* employees, Dick Kulpa, who became both Publisher and Editor-in-Chief of *Cracked*.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Under Kulpa, *Cracked* suffered from a lack of financing.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Combined with *Cracked*'s weakened distribution, circulation continued to drop precipitously, and Kulpa was forced to turn the magazine into a bi-monthly.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Dark Horse *Star Wars* comic editor Peet Janes briefly joined the staff, but financial difficulties at the magazine ended his tenure very quickly.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Later, after being offered a substantial pay cut, signature artist John Severin parted company with the magazine.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In 2004, Kulpa, new editors Scott Gosar and Marten Jallad, and now Promotions Editor Mark Van Woert, who had been with the magazine since 2000 as its webmaster, attempted one last resuscitation of the original title.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In an effort to generate publicity, Cheap Trick guitarist Rick Nielsen was named as the magazine's new "publisher," but this failed to spark interest.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The 365th and final issue featured an "Election Year" cover by science fiction artist Frank Kelly Freas, who had provided many of *Mad* magazine's covers from 1958–62.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] In early 2005, Kulpa sold *Cracked* to Teshkeel Media Group, a federation of Arab, Asian, and American investors, who announced plans to revive *Cracked* with a new editorial focus and redesign.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Its first steps included naming entrepreneur Monty Sarhan as both CEO and publisher.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Writer Neal Pollack was named "editor-at-large", and former editor Mort Todd was named a contributing editor.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] However, Todd quickly departed, complaining to *The Comics Journal* about low pay rates and work-for-hire issues of copyright.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Todd said, "With each visit to the offices I got more dispirited as I saw the direction the magazine was taking.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] As has been well publicized, Cracked was, instead of ripping off MAD, going to rip off Maxim...
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] A lot of 'revolutionary' humor ideas they've come up with are ones that have been overplayed for decades and ones I rejected for good reason 20 years ago [as Cracked's editor]".
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] On August 15, 2006, the revamped *Cracked* magazine finally appeared.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The first issue was a significant departure from *Cracked*'s previous incarnation, notably in its sharp reduction of comics and illustrated content.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The new format was more text-heavy, and was overtly indebted to modern "lad mags" like *Maxim*, *Stuff* and *FHM*, although the media website Gawker.com wrote, "Very little remains of the old *Cracked* – a *Mad* ripoff that had tread water in various incarnations for almost half a century.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] After three poor-selling issues, the failing magazine was canceled in February 2007.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] Citing distribution problems for its demise, editor Jay Pinkerton claimed that the remaining staff would be focusing its energies toward the *Cracked* website, as well as unspecified book projects.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] The company's website, Cracked.com, continued and has become known for its humorous lists and compilations, such as "6 Most Ridiculous Things People Claimed to Legally Own".
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] A book collection in that vein, *You Might Be a Zombie, and Other Bad News*, was published in 2010.
[src:ferret-legging/cracked-magazine] A two-volume history of the magazine, *If You're Cracked, You're Happy*, written by Mark Arnold, was published in June 2011.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Ferret-legging may have originated during the time when only the relatively wealthy in England were allowed to keep animals used for hunting, forcing poachers to hide their illicit ferrets in their trousers.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Following a brief resurgence in popularity during the 1970s, it has been described as a "dying sport", although a national ferret-legging event was held in Richmond, Virginia, US from 2003 to 2009.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In the sport of ferret-legging, competitors tie their trousers at the ankles before placing two ferrets inside and securely fastening their belts to prevent the ferrets from escaping.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Each competitor then stands in front of the judges for as long as he can.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Competitors cannot be drunk or drugged, nor can the ferrets be sedated.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In addition, competitors are not allowed to wear underwear beneath their trousers, which must allow the ferrets free access from one leg to the other, and the ferrets must have a full set of teeth that must not have been filed or otherwise blunted.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The winner is the person who lasts the longest.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The sport is said to involve very little "native skill", simply an ability to "have your tool bitten and not care".
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The former world champion, Reg Mellor, is credited with instituting the practice of wearing white trousers in ferret-legging matches, to better display the blood from the wounds caused by the animals.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Competitors can attempt, from outside their trousers, to dislodge the ferrets, but as the animals can maintain a strong hold for long periods, their removal can be difficult.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The ferrets are occasionally put inside the contestants' shirts in addition to their trousers.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] An attempt to introduce a female version of the sport—ferret busting, in which female contestants introduced ferrets down their blouses—proved unsuccessful.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The origin of ferret-legging is disputed.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The sport seems to have become popular among coal miners in Yorkshire, England, in the 1970s, though some Scots claim it gained popularity in Scotland.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The pastime gained attention in a humorous article written by Don Katz, entitled "King of the Ferret Leggers," in the October 1987 issue of *Outside* magazine.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Katz described ferrets as "having claws like hypodermic needles and teeth like number 16 carpet tacks".
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] James Howard of *The Fresno Bee* said Katz failed to explain why anyone would want to participate in a sport such as ferret-legging, but the article "offers a glimpse into the human need to challenge the edges of human endurance".
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In 1972, the ferret-legging record stood at 40 seconds.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] A few years later, the record had risen to over one minute, and eventually to 90 minutes.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In 1977, Edward Simpkins from the Isle of Wight set the new world record of five hours and ten minutes, although he only had one ferret in his trousers during the first four hours and two for the last seventy minutes.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Simpkins sustained two large bites during his record-breaking attempt, but continued to play a game of darts undeterred.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Retired miner Reg Mellor, from Barnsley, set the new world record time of five hours and twenty-six minutes on 5 July 1981 at the Annual Pennine Show at Holmfirth, Yorkshire.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] He had practised the sport since his youth, but had received no recognition until he set the new world record.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Mellor, who had hunted with ferrets in the dales outside Barnsley for many years, had grown accustomed to keeping them in his trousers to keep them warm and dry when out working in the rain.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Mellor's "trick" was to ensure that the ferrets were well-fed before they were inserted into his trousers.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In 1986, Mellor attempted to break his own record before a crowd of 2,500 spectators, intending to beat the "magic six-hour mark—the four-minute mile of ferret legging".
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] After five hours, most of the attendees had become bored and left; workmen arrived to dismantle the stage, despite Mellor's protests that he was on his way to a new record.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] According to Adrian Tame of the *Sunday Herald Sun*, Mellor retired after that experience, "disillusioned and broken-hearted," but with his dignity and manhood intact.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Mellor had hoped to organise an annual national competition held in his home town of Barnsley, and offered a prize of £100 to anyone who could beat him.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Frank Bartlett, a retired headmaster, and Christine Farnsworth, broke Mellor's record in 2010.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] The pair managed five hours and thirty minutes, raising £1,000 for the Whittington Community First Responders.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Ferret-legging has existed for centuries, but the sport made a brief resurgence in popularity during the 1970s.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] According to a 2005 report published in the English *Northern Echo* newspaper, whether due to a "lack of brave contestants or complaining wives", ferret-legging is now "a dying sport" that is being replaced by ferret racing, in which the animals race through a plastic pipe.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Although the sport is now uncommon, annual competitions were held at the Richmond Highland Games & Celtic Festival in Richmond, Virginia from 2003 through 2009.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] In 2007 the Manitoba Ferret Association held a ferret-legging competition in St.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Vital Park, Winnipeg, to raise money in support of the organization's shelter for homeless ferrets.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Marlene Blackburn, who works with the Ferret Rescue League to ensure that no ferrets are harmed in the sport, claims that during the years the competitions have been held in Richmond no contestant has ever been bitten, although some may get a few scratches.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] According to Kelly Yager of the Manitoba Ferret Association, the animals actually like small, confined spaces.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Jay Lugar, spokesman for the Richmond Highland Games & Celtic Festival, said ferrets are "generally very harmless, fun-loving creatures." Reg Mellor, however, commented that at their very worst, they can be "cannibals, things that live only to kill, that'll eat your eyes out to get at your brain".
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] *The Atlanta Journal*'s Scott Bernarde commented that anyone who has tried ferret-legging "will agree that falling off a mountain isn't all that bad." American sportswriter Rick Reilly of ESPN tried ferret-legging as part of his quest to find "the world's dumbest sport" for a book published in 2010.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Mellor made a brief appearance in the 1976 television documentary presented by actor and wrestler Brian Glover entitled *It's no joke living in Barnsley*, in which he demonstrated ferret-legging.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] During his appearance on *The Tonight Show with Jay Leno* in May 1996, actor Paul Hogan (*Crocodile Dundee*) spent much of the interview with Leno talking about ferret-legging, which he identified as "a new Australian Olympics event." In November 1992, the J.
[src:ferret-legging/ferret-legging] Walter Thompson advertising firm produced television commercials for the California State Lottery that compared keno with ferret-legging.
